<PageTitle>Optimized Render Tree Column Demo</PageTitle>

<div class="demo-description" style="margin:1.5rem 0; padding:1rem 1.25rem; background:#f7fafc; border-left:4px solid #ff9800; border-radius:4px; line-height:1.55; font-size:0.95rem;">
    <h3 style="margin-top:0; margin-bottom:0.75rem; font-size:1.25rem; color:#ff9800;">Why an Optimized Column?</h3>
    <p><strong>Goal:</strong> Reduce CPU, memory, and DOM pressure for data-heavy grids by eliminating avoidable costs: reflection lookups, repeated string building, excess elements, and unstable sequence numbers. This component packages 4 core optimizations into a reusable column.</p>
    <p><strong>Key Techniques:</strong></p>
    <ul style="margin:0.5rem 0 0.75rem 1.25rem; padding:0;">
        <li><em>Compiled Accessors:</em> <code>Property.Compile()</code> once → nanosecond property access vs hundreds of ns via reflection.</li>
        <li><em>Deterministic Sequences:</em> Single <code>int seq = 0; seq++</code> progression per cell maximizes diffing efficiency.</li>
        <li><em>Cached Class Strings:</em> Precomputed for small combination space (highlight/warning/error) instead of concatenating each render.</li>
        <li><em>Minimal DOM:</em> One wrapper element per cell; conditional attributes replace nested structural wrappers.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Benchmarks (Representative):</strong> Reflection vs compiled access often yields 10–30× speedup; cached class building removes thousands of transient string allocations; DOM reduction (4 → 1 element) divides layout/paint cost by ~4; overall full-grid rendering shows multi‑X improvements for large row counts.</p>
    <p><strong>Use Cases:</strong> High-frequency refresh dashboards, virtualization buffers, large analytics tables (&gt; 1k rows), realtime monitoring grids, mobile scenarios where DOM budget is tight.</p>
    <p><strong>Adoption Strategy:</strong> Start with naive columns for clarity; introduce optimized columns when profiler or DevTools show layout / scripting hotspots (long scripting tasks, high node counts, reclaimed memory spikes).</p>
    <p><strong>Trade‑Offs:</strong> Slightly more internal complexity (caching dictionary + compiled delegate). Avoid premature optimization for tiny grids (&lt;100 rows)—benefits scale with cell count.</p>
    <p><strong>Extensibility:</strong> Add conditional formatting, skeleton loading, or batched updates without violating optimizations (keep sequence discipline, reuse caches, avoid nested spans).</p>
    <p><strong>Outcome:</strong> Cleaner page markup (<code>&lt;OptimizedColumn ... /&gt;</code>) and consistent performance best practices applied everywhere automatically.</p>
</div>

<h3>Optimized Render Tree Column</h3>

<p>
    Demonstrates four critical performance optimizations: proper sequence numbering, 
    cached class computation, minimal DOM manipulation, and compiled expression accessors.
</p>

